Git Commands Learned
1. Repository Initialization & Setup
•	git init → Initialize a new Git repository
•	git clone → Copy a remote repository to local system
•	git config → Set Git configuration like username and email
________________________________________
2. Checking Status & History
•	git status → Shows current changes and staged/unstaged files
•	git log → Displays commit history of the repository
________________________________________
3. Staging & Saving Changes
•	git add → Stage changes for commit
•	git commit → Save changes to local repository
________________________________________
4. Remote Repository Management
•	git remote → Manage remote repository connections
•	git push → Upload local commits to remote repository
•	git pull → Fetch and merge changes from remote
•	git fetch → Download latest changes without merging
________________________________________
5. Branching & Navigation
•	git branch → Create or view branches
•	git checkout → Switch between branches or restore files
•	git switch → Modern way to switch branches
________________________________________
6. Advanced Git Concepts
•	git merge → Combine changes from another branch
•	git rebase → Reapply commits on top of another base
•	git cherry-pick → Apply a specific commit from another branch
________________________________________
7. Undo & Temporary Storage
•	git stash → Save uncommitted changes temporarily
•	git reset → Unstage or undo commits
•	git revert → Create a new commit to undo changes
________________________________________
Concept Comparison (Important Learning)
Git status vs Git log
•	git status → Shows working directory state (what changed)
•	git log → Shows commit history
________________________________________
Git checkout vs Git switch
•	git checkout → Old command (switch branches + restore files)
•	git switch → New, safer command (only for branch switching)
________________________________________
Git init vs Git clone
•	git init → Create a new empty repository
•	git clone → Copy existing repository from remote
________________________________________
Git rebase
•	Used to maintain a clean linear commit history
•	Moves your commits on top of another branch instead of merging
________________________________________
Git Fork (Concept)
•	A fork creates a personal copy of someone else’s repository on GitHub
•	Used in open-source contributions
•	You can modify freely and later create a pull request
________________________________________
Key Takeaways
•	Git helps in version control and collaboration
•	Branching allows parallel development
•	Remote commands connect local repo to GitHub
•	Rebase helps maintain clean commit history
